[normal] The Government ought to recall its obligations to c
[normal]omply with A
[normal]rticle 47 of the EU Charter of Fundamen
[normal]tal Rights when 
[normal]implementing
[normal] EU law, which provides that ‘legal aid shall be made available to those who lack sufficient resources in so far as such aid is necessary to ensur
[normal]e effective access to justice.’.  Importantly, Article 47 TEU does not include the
[normal] additional requirement of Article 6 ECHR that a fair hearing be provided in the determination of “civil rights and obligations”.  See 
[normal]DEB v 
[normal]Germany
[normal], 
[normal][2010] ECR I- 13849
[normal], 28.  
[normal] Several international and regional human rights treaties recognise access to 
[normal]free legal assistance as an essential component of the right to a fair trial.
[normal]  Although many of these focus on criminal justice, international law appears to mirror the requirements of the common law and the ECHR that legal assistance may be essential wher
[normal]e otherwise a hearing would be rendered unfair
[normal].  For example, In its 
[normal]General C
[normal]omment No. 32 (2007), the Human Rights Committee acknowledged that “the availability or absence of legal assistance often determines whether or not a person can access the releva
[normal]nt proceedings or participate in them in a meaningful way”, and encouraged States to provide free legal aid not only in criminal proceedings, but also in other cases where individuals do not have sufficient means to pay for it.    
