[normal]That prisoners are in a vulnerable position and subject to the absolute coercive
[normal] power of the State is recognised in most international human rights instruments and within the domestic law.  As Lord Woolf recognises in his report, 
[normal]Prison Disturbances: 
[normal]‘a prisoner, as a result of bein
[normal]g in prison, is particularly vu
[normal]lnerable to arbitrary
[normal] and unlawful action’ (1991), 
[normal]para
[normal] 14.293.   See also 
[normal]R v Board of Visitors of 
[normal]Hull
[normal] Prison 
[normal][1979] 1 QB 425 and 
[normal]Raymond v Honey 
[normal][1983] 1 AC 1.
[normal] For example, many of the serious issues identified in the Joint Committee on Human Rights report on deaths in cu
[normal]stody about the treatment of prisoners – segregation, access to healthcare and restraint to take a few – would now be treatment issues for which prisoners would no longer be able to access criminal legal aid to lodge a complaint, even if it had been shown 
[normal]that a remedy was not possible using the alternative mechanisms identified in the First Consultation Paper.  See Third Report of Session 2004-05, 
[normal]Deaths in Custody, 
